<!--DOCTYPE section SYSTEM "file:/opt/share/xml/Oxygen/docbook/dtd/docbookx.dtd"--><ns3280:section xmlns:ns3280="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.networkServices.nfs.nfsServerStartStop">

  <ns3281:title xmlns:ns3281="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Starting and stopping the NFS client</ns3281:title>
  <ns3282:para xmlns:ns3282="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The NFS server is usually started in the boot script. Like the NFS client, 
    <ns3283:command xmlns:ns3283="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">nfs</ns3283:command>, you can also start, stop, restart, reload, 
    force-reload and query the status of <ns3284:command xmlns:ns3284="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">nfsserver</ns3284:command>. 
    For example, to start the NFS server you would use
    <ns3285:cmdsynopsis xmlns:ns3285="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns3286:command xmlns:ns3286="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
nfsserver start      
    </ns3286:command></ns3285:cmdsynopsis>
    and to force a reload of all the <ns3287:filename xmlns:ns3287="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">/etc/exports</ns3287:filename> entries you can use
    <ns3288:cmdsynopsis xmlns:ns3288="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns3289:command xmlns:ns3289="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
nfsserver force-reload      
    </ns3289:command></ns3288:cmdsynopsis>
  </ns3282:para>
</ns3280:section>